      <!-- First section of the article-->
      <section id="lab-article-section-1">
        <div id="lab-article-section-1-icon" class="icon">
          <!-- Enclose the icon image for the section. -->
	  <img src="../images/introduction.jpg" />
	</div>


        <!-- The heading for the section can be enclosed in a 
        div tag. -->
	<div id="lab-article-section-1-heading" class="heading">
	Introduction
	</div>
				
	<!-- Write the section content inside a paragraph 
        element, You can also include images with <img> tag -->
	<div id="lab-article-section-1-content" class="content">
<p align="justify">
<br>	
	<p>
	<strong>
	When a chemical reaction occurs, its speed depends on the amounts of reactants present in a certain manner called a rate law. How do we know what is the rate law for a particular reaction? How do we measure speeds? One can monitor distinguishable properties of the reactants to follow a reaction over time. Optical activity is one such remarkable property that can be used if the molecular structure of a reactant is asymmetric. Cane sugar is such a molecule.
	
	
	</tr>
	

	
	<object id="player" classid="clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000" name="player" width="620" height="200">
		<param name="movie" value="media/mediaplayer/player-viral.swf" />
		<param name="allowfullscreen" value="true" />
		<param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" />
                <param name='loop' value='true'/>
		<param name="flashvars" value="file=chem.flv&image=media/mediaplayer/preview.png" />
		<embed
			type="application/x-shockwave-flash"
			id="player2"
			name="player2"
			src="media/mediaplayer/player-viral.swf" 
			width="550" 
			height="386"
			allowscriptaccess="always" 
			allowfullscreen="true"
			flashvars="file=chem.flv&image=media/mediaplayer/preview.png" />

	</object>
        
	
	</strong>	
	

	

	<div id="qtview" ><div class="qtcontent" id="MASKED-clicktoplay"><p>
	</div></div>	
	<strong>
	<p>
	In presence of acid it hydrolyzes to glucose and fructose:<br><br>

	C<sub>12</sub>H<sub>22</sub>O<sub>11</sub> + H<sub>2</sub>O = C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>12</sub>O<sub>6</sub> (glucose) + C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>12</sub>O<sub>6</sub> 		(fructose)<br><br>

	and we can follow the reaction by measuring how a plane of polarization of light passing through the solution undergoes rotation.

	This experiment has great historical significance. In 1850, Wilhelmy carried out this experiment to study the kinetics of hydrolysis (inversion) of cane sugar 		catalyzed by acids. It is an early example of studies of reaction rates in homogeneous systems and the concept of the velocity of reaction was developed during 	these studies. This work was the precursor of later studies of the temperature effect on reaction velocity by van’t Hoff, Arrhenius, and Ostwald. </p>
	<img align=center src="images/glucose_a.jpeg" height="200" width="500"></img>

	
	<br/><br/><br/>
	</strong>
	
	</div>
      </section>
		

